course_aims:
This course is an introduction to business analysis, financial statement analysis and valuation, that demonstrates and applies a business analysis framework and valuation using financial statement data. The main purposes of the course are to:

Understand the basic techniques of financial analysis and business valuation using a structured approach;

Appreciate the importance to valuation of the linkages between industry and strategy, financial statement information, forecasting, capital market participants, and the estimation of the intrinsic value of a common share;

Understand how financial statements are used in the valuation process;

Understand how to use different valuation models and their benefits and limitations;

Develop the skills to prepare a valuation and stock recommendation and justify it in terms of the business context.

This is the course for you if you want exposure to the state of the art approach to valuing the shares of a company. Valuation is a highly speculative undertaking. This course introduces a systematic approach to valuation that reduces the input of pure speculation by emphasising the importance of knowing the business, the business environment, and the appropriate data and valuation model to use for the type of company you are trying to value. Some students are impatient with the upfront, fundamental 'business and accounting' analysis requirements, but beware the valuation failures of the financial analyst who does not thoroughly understand the company's fundamentals.

You will leave this course with a business analysis and valuation report that is the basis of a buy-sell recommendation for a share of common stock for a traded company. High quality reports demonstrate an understanding of the business analysis and valuation process to potential employers. If your report is high quality, it will therefore help you demonstrate that you have this knowledge to future employers.
